### Production Rules (Additional)

**Target word count:** 1,100-1,300 words. Do not pad. Every sentence must add information. If the full outline is covered in 1,050 words, that is acceptable. Do not stretch to hit a number.

**Tone:** Knowledgeable friend giving practical advice. Not academic. Not promotional. Not listicle-style. The reader should feel like they are getting the frank version that an experienced renter would tell them over coffee.

**Sentence structure:** Short declarative sentences. Two short sentences over one compound sentence. Avoid "which" clauses and nested phrases. If a sentence is longer than 25 words, split it.

**Paragraph length:** 2-4 sentences maximum. Never more than four sentences in a block. Dense paragraphs reduce dwell time on mobile. Single-sentence paragraphs are acceptable for emphasis.

**No filler introductions:** The first sentence of the article must contain the primary keyword and begin answering the query. Do not open with "If you have a dog, you know the challenge of..." or any variation of restating the premise. Begin with information.

**Section openings:** Every H2 section opens with its answer or key takeaway in the first sentence. No context-setting, no background, no lead-up paragraphs. The answer comes first. Context follows.

**Numbers and data:** Every dollar figure, rent range, statistic, or factual claim must include "(as of [Quarter Year])" adjacent to the claim. If a number cannot be verified, write [VERIFY] inline and do not fabricate.

**Tables:** Use markdown table formatting. Keep tables to two per article maximum. Label each table with a plain-text caption above it.

**Lists:** Use bulleted or numbered lists only when presenting three or more parallel items. Do not use a list for two items. Do not nest lists.

